I need a dollar, dollar

[Break]

Middle and lower classes have been breaking their backs trying to secure a safer life that they rarely succeeded to achieve and while they were at it , a crisis hits them hard every decade and throws them back further away from financial safety. All financial systems in the world has proven that anything below high class is prone to poverty, both capitalism and socialism have failed to provide for those who are in need.

comment: Can we start showcasing artists like this on all big streaming, media, and award shows, instead of the 90% of garbage mainstream artists that get all the attention, acclaim, and money? I think people fail to realize that Music and Song Writing is an ART FORM! We're all too dumb and distracted with these stick figure and color by number artists, that we are basically oblivious and neglectful to all the da Vincis, Monets, Warhols, and Van Goghs of the music industry. comment: I'm aware of the lyrics dude.  In the song he asked if the answer to his problems were in the bottle.  That is not an endorsement of becoming an alcoholic loser.  It is merely an acknowledgement of the realities that a lot of people have to deal with.  Obviously the correct way to deal with tough times is to keep working, doing your best, and doing whatever you have to do. Asking for a dollar is a reflection of a guy going through tough times, not advocating panhandling. I don't think you get it
author: Matt Wilemon Wilemon

comment:
I don't like your condescending attitude. Have you listened to the lyrics? He sings about finding his answer in a bottle and the refrain is first asking, then demanding a dollar. If that's not being a wino and panhandling to you then you may require a dictionary. His lyrics come on share your dollar with me
go ahead share your dollar with me
come on share your dollar give me your dollar
share your dollar with me
come on share your dollar with me
author: Kodack Gaming

comment: I think you are reading too much into it and are adding things to the song that nobody is actually.  It is simply a song about a guy who has had a rough life, lost his job, and doesn't quite know what to do.  I think in this world of low wages and high unemployment that a lot of people can relate to what he is saying.  Nobody is talking about being a panhandling, drunk, or a victim, or any of that stuff except for you.  I think the meaning of this song has clearly gone over your head.
author: Matt Wilemon Wilemon

comment: I can't believe people listen to this song and aren't outraged. A song about begging for handouts, becoming a wino, and turning yourself into a victim instead of trying to get a job and make your own way in the world. This song has done more damage to a positive black image than very rapper on the west coast combined. At least someone singing about illegal work is still singing about work, not acting victimized and becoming a washed out, pan handling, wino.

comment:
an/a is based on the probounciation mate. euro is pronounced something like "yuro" meaning it starts on a consonant sound, thus it is not an euro, it is in fact a euro. Variations may occur depending on accent and so forth, but a euro is no more incorrect than "an hour" (h is muted, so the word starts with a vocal), or "a year" even though "y" is a consonant. 
Conclusion: Don't rage, especially not if you don't know what your talking about.

A Dollar aint what it was anymore, you need to be more specific.The dollar lost value against the euroBy the end of February, the euro was worth $1.3463.
2009 - The dollar fell 20% thanks to debt fears. By December, the euro was worth $1.43.
2008 - The dollar strengthened 22% as businesses hoarded dollars during the global financial crisis. By year end, the euro was worth $1.39.2002-2007 - The dollar fell 40% as the U.S. debt grew 60%. In 2002, a euro was worth $.87 vs $1.44 by December 2007.
